[2]
Date: Thu 3 Jul 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters Heath eLine, Thu 3 Jul 2003 [edited]
<http://www.reutershealth.com/archive/2003/07/03/eline/links/20030703elin015.html>

Germany: Dengue Fever Cases Increasing Among Returning Tourists
---------------------------------------------------------------
The number of dengue fever cases in Germany is dramatically rising as more
people go on holiday to places where the infection is endemic, according to
public health authorities. The Robert Koch Institute in Berlin reported
this week that cases of the viral infection rose to 230 in 2002, up from 60
the year before.
The disease, which is transmitted through mosquito bites, is characterized
by high fever, bone and muscle pain and -- in the most serious cases --
hemorrhage and fatal shock. Experts estimate that about 50 million people
are affected by dengue each year, with about 5 percent of patients dying of
the illness. The Robert Koch Institute warned that there could be a large
number of unregistered cases in Germany, as many people who develop a short
fever after returning home from holiday might not be tested for dengue.
The areas that researchers named as sources of European infections include
the holiday regions of Southeast Asia and the western Pacific. Experts at
the Robert Koch Institute estimate that 42 percent of German cases are
among people who had been on holiday in Southeast Asia, primarily Thailand.
The disease incubates for 2 to 10 days before a mild fever develops. Around
10 percent of those infected develop high fever, with a strong headache and
accompanying aches and pains. In a small number of cases, the illness
develops into dengue hemorrhagic fever and dengue shock syndrome. This is
mostly observed in children younger than 15 years old.
[Byline: Hannah Cleaver]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
