[3]
Date: Fri 4 Jul 2003
From: Alain Berlioz <aberlioz@pasteur.nc>
Source: Dengue Surveillance Network, New Caledonia, No.7, 2003 [edited]

New Caledonia: Surveillance Report No. 7 (Activity for June 2003)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Number of patients investigated : 742 (since 2 Jun 2003).
New positive cases since 2 Jun 2003 (aggregate 2003) : Dengue serotype 1
(PCR) : 28 (539) Unidentified type (IgM only) : 287 (1778) Total : 315 (2317).
As of Tue 1 Jul 2003, 5147 cases had been reported to the Department of
Health and Social Affairs (DASS) since the beginning of the year, including
2317 confirmed by laboratory tests at the New Caledonia Pasteur Institute.
No new deaths from dengue fever have been reported since early June (13
since 1 Jan 2003).
The decrease in the number of cases, which began in May, has been confirmed
and undoubtedly shows a downward trend in the current outbreak. This can be
explained by the effectiveness of the various prevention and vector control
measures taken, as well as by the arrival of the cool season, which is not
favorable to breeding of _Aedes_ mosquitoes. In Noumea, entomological
surveillance in June showed very low indexes, which confirm this situation.
This apparent calm must be balanced against the undoubtedly growing number
of unreported cases and so is not a sign of the end of transmission, as the
still significant number of cases confirmed each week (45 for the Week of
23 to 29 Jun 2003) prove. Moreover, these recent cases have been widely
spread out over the whole Territory.
In this period in which other viral diseases circulate respiratory
syncytial virus (RSV) infection, others are likely to arrive (influenza),
and during which a few cases of leptospirosis have been confirmed (in June
on the east coast), the clinical diagnosis of dengue fever becomes less
specific.
Put on hold during the height of the epidemic, sentinel activity again
becomes relevant and will allow [identification of] those foci that are
still active, once the warm season returns.
--
Alain Berlioz-Arthaud
Laboratoire de Biologie Medicale
Institut PASTEUR de Nouvelle Caledonie
BP 61, 98845 Noumea, New Caledonia
<aberlioz@pasteur.nc>
