<http://cubanet.org/CNews/y03/jul03/03a2.htm>

Cuba: Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever Reported in Havana
-------------------------------------------------
The ecological association NATURPAZ reported that there have been outbreaks
of diseases such as leptospirosis, dengue hemorrhagic fever, mycotic
stomatitis, pneumonia, and diarrhea in the Cuban capital. Osmani Garcia
Ballart, President of NATURPAZ, commented that young children and residents
of suburbs and small towns are more susceptible to illness.
The municipalities most affected by dengue hemorrhagic fever are Habana
Vieja [Old Havana] and Habana Centro [Central Havana], while leptospirosis
has been reported in the municipalities of Arroyo Naranjo and San Miguel
del Padron. Stomatitis has been detected in La Lisa and Marianao, and cases
of pneumonia and diarrheal diseases have been detected in most of the
municipalities of the capital.
The ecologist concluded that these diseases can be prevented by measures
such as water treatment, installation of plumbing systems, cleaning of the
city, and garbage and debris collection, but that these measures will not
be implemented until the [head of the government] gives the order.
--
Paul Lamot
<PL@pandora.be>
[Dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) occurs as a minor component of outbreaks of
dengue fever, usually but not always following the appearance of a new
serotype in an endemic region. In 2002, 2999 cases of dengue fever and 12
cases of DHF (one death) were reported to PAHO by the Cuban Ministry of
Health (serotype of the virus not stated). Up to week 15 of 2003 no cases
of dengue fever or DHF were reported from Cuba to PAHO. The statement from
NATURPAZ citing an outbreak of DHF must be treated with caution, since it
fails to mention presence of dengue fever or indicate that eradication of
the _Aedes_ mosquito vector is the principal defence against dengue fever.
Further information from an informed source would be appreciated. - Mod.CP]
